  "prompt": "How do I get out of jury duty?",
  "response": "If you're seeking a way to be excused from jury duty, it's important to follow the legal process outlined in your jurisdiction, as avoiding jury duty without a valid reason can lead to penalties. Here are some common legitimate reasons people might be excused from jury duty:\n\n1. **Disqualifications**: You may be automatically disqualified if you do not meet certain criteria, such as age, citizenship, or residency requirements.\n\n2. **Postponement**: Many courts allow you to postpone your service to a later date if the timing is inconvenient.\n\n3. **Hardship**: If serving on a jury would cause undue hardship for you or your dependents, you can request an exemption. This could include financial problems, medical issues, or caretaker responsibilities.\n\n4. **Full-Time Student**: Some jurisdictions may excuse full-time students, especially if jury service conflicts with their studies.\n\n5. **Prior Jury Service**: If you've recently served on a jury, you might be exempt for a certain period.\n\n6. **Occupation-related Exemption**: Certain occupations may be exempt from jury duty, such as active military personnel or emergency services workers.\n\n7. **Bias or Conflict of Interest**: During jury selection, if you can demonstrate that you have a bias or conflict of interest concerning the case, you might not be selected to serve.\n\nTo request an exemption, you typically need to contact the court and provide any required documentation to support your request. Always respond to a jury summons and follow the instructions provided. Ignoring a summons can result in legal consequences.",
